We treat as a sensitivity signature that captures how the query–passage similarity responds to randomized perturbations. From these probe gradients, we derive two complementary statistics: representational consistency, which measures directional agreement across perturbations, and dispersion risk, which captures lower-tail instability.
As directly computing gradients with respect to all retriever parameters is computationally prohibitive for ranking, we probe only the small subset to obtain a lightweight sensitivity signature, following prior work that uses parameter subsets for scalable gradient-based influence analysis [pruthi2020tracin]. This view is also related to Fisher-score style representations, which characterize an input by its parameter gradients [jaakkola1999fisher].
