3.5 Towards Implementation Efficiency
Although our formulation is defined over , a practical deployment would instantiate as a bounded first-stage candidate pool rather than the full corpus. One may first retrieve a buffer of top- candidates with , estimate the gate on this pool, and apply stochastic probing only to the decision-critical upper-tail candidates before selecting the final top-. The additional defence overhead then depends mainly on the bounded pool size , rather than directly on the full corpus size, while remaining consistent with the score-gating intuition in Sec. 3.3.
4 Experiments
4.1 Experimental Setups
Datasets and corpus poisoning methods.
Following the implementation in [Wang2025JointGCG], we evaluate on MS MARCO [bajaj2016msmarco], Natural Questions (NQ) [kwiatkowski2019naturalquestions], and HotpotQA [yang2018hotpotqa]. Our corpus poisoning methods include PoisonedRAG [Zou2025PoisonedRAGUSENIX], LIAR-RAG [liarrag], and Joint-GCG [Wang2025JointGCG]. For each dataset, we sample 100 evaluation queries, and each query is associated with 50 clean passages.
Retrieval-stage settings.
For retrieval-stage experiments, we consider three dense retrievers: Contriever [izacard2022contriever], DPR [karpukhin2020dpr], and BGE [xiao2023cpack]. We use a pooled-poison protocol, where all poisoned passages for the same query are added to the clean pool. For each query, the retriever returns a Top- list with . We evaluate ProGRank under four factors: perturbation repeats , probe layer , perturbation type (encoder dropout, token dropout, or their mixture), and retriever backbone. Here, denotes the probed LayerNorm module, and for dispersion risk we fix , , and . Results in Fig. 2, 3, and 5 are averaged over these settings, while Fig. 6 reports the corresponding ablations. The ablations show that performance stabilizes around , performs best overall, and mixed perturbation is the strongest setting. These choices are then used in the downstream generation experiments. To avoid data snooping, retrieval-stage analysis and configuration selection use a random 20% query split, and downstream generation uses the remaining 80%.
