Downstream generation settings.
For downstream generation, we use Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct, Llama-3-8B-Instruct, and Mistral-7B-Instruct v0.2 as generators, all with the same decoding configuration. For ProGRank, as in the retrieval analysis, we vary the retriever backbone among Contriever, DPR, and BGE. We fix the retrieval depth , the perturbation repeat , mixed perturbation, and probe layer . Unless otherwise specified, we report results averaged over generators, retriever backbones.
We report substring-based attack success rate (ASR), judge-based ASR, and substring-based accuracy (ACC). Let denote the generated response for query , let denote the ground-truth correct answer, and let denote the attacker-targeted incorrect answer. Before evaluation, both model outputs and reference answers are normalized by lowercasing and removing punctuation and extra whitespace. We define substring-based ASR as , where if the normalized response contains but not . We define substring-based ACC as , where if the normalized response contains but not . Judge-based ASR is computed using a fixed deterministic LLM judge, Llama-Guard-3-8B [meta2024llamaguard3], which receives the query, the ground-truth correct answer, the attacker-targeted incorrect answer, and the model output, and assigns one label from {ATTACK, CORRECT, OTHER}; judge-based ASR is then the fraction of responses labeled ATTACK.
Besides these end-to-end robustness metrics, we also evaluate clean utility using benchmark-specific metrics. Following the standard protocol for each dataset, we report token-level F1 on HotpotQA, exact match (EM) on NQ, and ROUGE-L F1 on MS MARCO.
Compute.
All experiments were conducted on an NVIDIA DGX Spark.
