4.2 Downstream Generation Analysis
Under the downstream generation setting defined in Sec. 4.1, we evaluate ProGRank against the undefended baseline and compare it with representative corpus-poisoning defences, namely GRADA [zheng2025grada], GMTP [kim2025gmtp], and RAGuard [kolhe2025raguard]. These baselines are selected from Tab. 1 based on code availability.
Tab. 2 reports the main end-to-end robustness results. ProGRank achieves the lowest macro-average judge-based ASR on all three datasets, reaching on HotpotQA, NQ, and MS MARCO. It also achieves the lowest macro-average substring-based ASR on all three datasets, with on HotpotQA, on NQ, and on MS MARCO. In terms of clean utility, ProGRank achieves the highest macro-average ACC on HotpotQA, while GRADA performs best on NQ and RAGuard performs best on MS MARCO. As shown in Tab. 4, RAGuard is about slower than ProGRank on average due to repeated leave-one-out verification. The reported ProGRank latency is measured on the actual experimental pipeline, with all retrieved candidates reranked per query. Overall, ProGRank offers the strongest robustness and a substantially better efficiency–robustness trade-off than RAGuard in our evaluation.
Tab. 3 evaluates ProGRank under ProGRank-based evasive attacks. The macro-average results are on HotpotQA, on NQ, and on MS MARCO in terms of substring-based ASR, judge-based ASR, and ACC, respectively. These results suggest that ProGRank retains robustness under the adaptive attack configurations considered in this work, especially on HotpotQA and NQ.
Tab. 5 reports clean utility. ProGRank achieves the best EM on NQ, while the baseline and RAGuard perform better on HotpotQA, and GRADA gives the best ROUGE-L F1 on MS MARCO. Overall, this indicates a dataset-dependent trade-off between robustness and clean-task utility.
5 Conclusion
We presented ProGRank, a post hoc, training-free retriever-side defence against corpus poisoning in dense-retriever RAG. ProGRank stress-tests query–passage pairs under mild randomized perturbations and reranks them using probe-gradient instability signals computed on a small fixed parameter subset, instantiated in our experiments as a LayerNorm module at layer . Rather than assuming that all poisoned passages are intrinsically unstable, ProGRank targets a practically important subset of optimization-driven poisoning attacks whose retrievability relies on perturbation-sensitive matching signals. Across three datasets, multiple dense retrievers, and representative poisoning attacks, ProGRank consistently reduces poisoned Top- exposure and achieves the lowest macro-average judge-based ASR in end-to-end evaluation, while remaining effective under the adaptive attack settings considered in this work.
